hwsim hit MAX_STEPS=200M before reaching SLUB/NR_IRQS/clint/BogoMIPS,
but the trajectory matches silicon's hybrid build exactly up to this
point. No M-FU stuck/wrong-result events.

== Silicon mdstress (commit e395a2a, riski5-core-mdstress) ==

Per docs/perf/mdstress-silicon-2026-05-05.log:
  CMTC=65 frozen across multiple flash cycles (deterministic).
  core_pc frozen at 0x000000F0 = mulFailL.
  Decoded: 'B' boot byte + 9 successful MUHDSR. iterations + 1 'F'
  failure byte. The 10th iteration's `mul x3, x1, x2` (with
  identically reloaded x1=0x12345678, x2=0x100, expected
  0x45678000) returned a wrong value.

== Conclusion ==

Same iterative `mulDivFUIterative` source code:
  hwsim   — boots Linux through `Kernel command line:` cleanly,
            runs hundreds of MUL/DIV ops via printk's number()
            formatter, no failures.
  silicon — fails deterministically on the 10th identical MUL with
            same operands.

The bug is in the Quartus → Cyclone II synthesis of the iterative
FSM. Most likely candidates (deterministic 10-iter pattern):
  (a) Mealy-state register initialisation race on FSM re-entry
      that needs N MdIdle → MdBusyMul → MdDone → MdIdle cycles
      to manifest. Some prior MdMul launches leave residual
      state in `prodReg` that contaminates the 10th launch.
  (b) Quartus's mealy-state encoding for `MdPhase` introduces a
      transient invalid encoding that occasionally aliases a
      different launch path.
  (c) `Index 32` counter wraparound at maxBound has an edge case
      under Quartus's state-machine extraction that the Clash
      simulator doesn't model (Clash sim treats Index N as a
      clamped Unsigned with strict bounds checking; Quartus may
      lower it differently).

The hybrid `mulDivFUMulComb` (combinational MUL via DSP, iterative
DIV) workaround already lands in master (commit ee47123) and lets
silicon Linux boot to the scheduler-idle state where IRQs fire and
the kernel runs CFS load-tracking but no init exists to run.
Replacing iterative DIV with Newton-Raphson DSP-backed division
(task #59 follow-up) would eliminate the iterative FSM entirely.
